3D Magnetic Sensorc back to ToC or Class ToC

3D Magnetic Sensorc back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-OOSMP#_3DMagneticSensor

Capable of measuring 3D, linear and rotational movement. The sensor realizes an accurate three-dimensional sensing with extremely low power consumption. Capable of detecting the magnetic field in the x, y, and z-direction, the sensor is ideally suited for the measurement of linear, rotation or 3 dimensional movements.
has super-classes
Magnetic Position Sensor Magnetic Position Sensor c

a h mandatory core service i d dc back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#AH_mandatory_core_service_IDD

Class of all Interface Design Descriptions (IDDs) of mandatory Arrowwhead core services. While the class AH_mandatory_core_service contains the mandatory core services only as instances, this class contains classes of the IDDs of each single mandatory core service as subclasses (not only as instances). Since each AH Local Cloud runs one instance of each mandatory core service, each of these services has to be documented by an AH service documentation, i.e. at least by a SD and a IDD. So the IDD is an individual document for each mandatory core service in each single Local Cloud. Hence, all IDDs of a certain mandatory core service will be individuals of the corresponding IDD class.
has super-classes
a h core service i d d c
has sub-classes
a h authorization control service i d d c, a h orchestration service i d d c, a h service discovery service i d d c, a h store management service i d d c, a h token generation service i d d c

a h service documentation documentc back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#AH_service_documentation_document

Document belonging to the documentation of an Arrowhead Service. There are four types of documents for Arrowhead service documentations: - Service Description - Interface Design Description - Communication Profile - Semantic Profile. The central documents are IDDs. They document the implementation of a certain service based on a certain communication technology (communication, encoding, data format) and a certain information model. The Service Description contains a more general description of the service, without the link to a specific communication technology or information model. Communication Profiles and Semantic Profiles are optional documents for a service documentation. They can be seen as modules of an IDD, since they can describe the communication technolopgy and the information model of a service implementation as external documents. If they exist, the IDD refers to them instead of declaring these contents by themselfes. That is, CP and SP are useful if different service implementations use the same CP and SP - then their IDDs can refer to one and the same CP or SP document.
has super-classes
documentation document c
has sub-classes
communication profile c p c, interface design description i d d c, semantic profile s p c, service description s d c
is in domain of
is part of service doc op

Infineon offers a family of angle sensors based on integrated Magneto Resistive (ixMR) technologies. Technologies include today iGMR and AMR. Chemical Polishingc back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-SO#Chemical_Polishing

The chemical polishing process or chemical mechanical planarization (CMP) is a process whereby a chemical reaction increases the mechanical removal rate of a material. CMP is commonly used to polish off high spots on wafers or films deposited on wafers, flattening the film or wafer, referred to as planarization. The chemical reaction that increases the mechanical removal rate is commonly tailored to provide a higher removal rate of one material versus another material. The chemical action in CMP helps to achieve higher selectivity's of one material to another than a strictly mechanical process would provide.
has super-classes
Workshop c

constrained devicec back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#Constrained_device

A constrained device is a device in the sense of an service-oriented architecture that is restricted in terms of processing capabilities (speed, complexity of operations), memory and power supply. The concept constrained device was introduced in the context of the Internet of Things (IoT) and refers for example to sensor devices, location devices, switches etc. which are connected by low-power wireless communication technologies like BLE, ZigBee, Z-Wave etc., have a battery on board that should last for two to three years and which are (very) small in physical size.

device c

illumination device c, sensor device c, switch device c

Depositionc back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-SO#Deposition

The deposition process, or chemical vapor deposition (CVD) is a process whereby a fiolm is deposited by reacting chemicals together in the gaseous or vapor phase to form a film. The gases or vapors utilized for CVD are compounds that contain the element to be deposited and that may be inducted to react with a substrate or other gas(es) to deposit a film. The CVD reactoin may be thermally activated, plasma induced, plasma enhanced CVD or activated by light in photon induced CVD.

Diffusionc back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-SO#Diffusion

Diffusion is a process whereby a substance redistributes from an area of relatively high concentration to an area of relatively low concentration due to random thermal motion. Infineons DPS310 is a miniaturized digital barometric pressure sensor which offers high accuracy and low current consumption, and is capable of measuring both pressure and temperature. The small package and low energy consumption make DPS310 ideal for mobile applications and wearable devices.

Digital-Factory-Systemc back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AT#Digital-Factory-System

The term "Digital Factory" is used in different meanings today and should hence not longer be used. It should be replaced by more specific terms like "Digital Factory Planning system" or "Digital Factory Twin". Originally, Digital Factory referred to software tools for computer-aided planning, design, engineering and simulation of production, manufacturing, or assembly systems. These tools supplemented CAD-based tools for factory layout planning and tools for computer-aided tools for production engineering (work plan preparation, production process planning) and were glued together with them to PLM software suites. As today even CAD-based layout planning and process planning tools are "digital" and refer to the factory, the terms "Digital Factory tool" and "Production Engineering tool" more and more converge. At the same time, automation vendors start to use the concept "Digital Factory" to address online monitoring and control tools for production systems. In this meaning, the term is a synonym for "Digital Factory Twin" or "Digital Twin of a Factory". The important difference between these two meanings is the phase in the life cycle in which the tool is used: Manufacturing Planning / Eingineering is conducted mainly in the first two lifecycle phases in which the product (type, class) is created, designed, and engineered, as well as the corresponding production system. The online monitoring and control is conducted during the third phase, in which the product individuals are produced on the existing production system. Hartwig Baumgaertel, 2018-11-12
has super-classes
i t system c

indutrial sectorc back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-PWR#IndutrialSector

The collection of all localized groups of enterprises that are producers of industrial commodities, in which each such group together forms the major industrial sector for the region. 'Industrial commodities' includes MechanicalDevices and basic industrial materials. Examples include 'the world industrial sector', the 'industrial sector of China'. The Chinese water pump industry would not be an exemplar of IndustrialEconomicSector but would rather be a sub-industry (see subIndustries) of it. On the other hand, chinese water pump manufacturers would be considered groupMembers of 'the industrial sector of China'. This classification is done by The Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) is an industry taxonomy developed in 1999 by MSCI and Standard & Poor's (S&P) for use by the global financial community. The GICS structure consists of 11 sectors, 24 industry groups, 68 industries and 157 sub-industries[1] into which S&P has categorized all major public companies
Is defined by
http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr

m q t tc back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AT#MQTT

MQTT[1] (Message Queuing Telemetry Transport) is an ISO standard (ISO/IEC PRF 20922)[2] publish-subscribe-based messaging protocol. It works on top of the TCP/IP protocol. It is designed for connections with remote locations where a "small code footprint" is required or the network bandwidth is limited. The publish-subscribe messaging pattern requires a message broker. Andy Stanford-Clark of IBM and Arlen Nipper of Cirrus Link authored the first version of the protocol in 1999.[3] The specification does not specify the meaning of "small code footprint" or the meaning of "limited network bandwidth". Thus, the protocol's availability for use depends on the context. In 2013, IBM submitted MQTT v3.1 to the OASIS specification body with a charter that ensured only minor changes to the specification could be accepted.[4] MQTT-SN[5] is a variation of the main protocol aimed at embedded devices on non-TCP/IP networks, such as ZigBee. Historically, the "MQ" in "MQTT" came from IBM's MQ Series message queuing product line.[6] However, queuing itself is not required to be supported as a standard feature in all situations.[7] Alternative protocols include the Advanced Message Queuing Protocol (AMQP), Streaming Text Oriented Messaging Protocol (STOMP), the IETF Constrained Application Protocol,[8] XMPP,[9][10] DDS,[11] OPC UA,[12] and Web Application Messaging Protocol (WAMP). (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MQTT)
has super-classes
o s i 5 7 application protocol c
has sub-classes
m q t t non t c p i p based c, m q t t t c p i p based c

Observationc back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: http://www.w3.org/ns/sosa/Observation

Act of carrying out an (Observation) Procedure to estimate or calculate a value of a property of a FeatureOfInterest. Links to a Sensor to describe what made the Observation and how; links to an ObservableProperty to describe what the result is an estimate of, and to a FeatureOfInterest to detail what that property was associated with.
Act of carrying out an (Observation) Procedure to estimate or calculate a value of a property of a FeatureOfInterest. Links to a Sensor to describe what made the Observation and how; links to an ObservableProperty to describe what the result is an estimate of, and to a FeatureOfInterest to detail what that property was associated with.
Is defined by
http://www.w3.org/ns/sosa/
Example
The activity of estimating the intensity of an Earthquake using the Mercalli intensity scale is an Observation as is measuring the moment magnitude, i.e., the energy released by said earthquake.

IRI: http://www.w3.org/ns/sosa/Procedure

A workflow, protocol, plan, algorithm, or computational method specifying how to make an Observation, create a Sample, or make a change to the state of the world (via an Actuator). A Procedure is re-usable, and might be involved in many Observations, Samplings, or Actuations. It explains the steps to be carried out to arrive at reproducible results.
A workflow, protocol, plan, algorithm, or computational method specifying how to make an Observation, create a Sample, or make a change to the state of the world (via an Actuator). A Procedure is re-usable, and might be involved in many Observations, Samplings, or Actuations. It explains the steps to be carried out to arrive at reproducible results.
Is defined by
http://www.w3.org/ns/sosa/
Example
The measured wind speed differs depending on the height of the sensor above the surface, e.g., due to friction. Consequently, procedures for measuring wind speed define a standard height for anemometers above ground, typically 10m for meteorological measures and 2m in Agrometeorology. This definition of height, sensor placement, and so forth are defined by the Procedure.
has super-classes

is in range of

qualityc back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-PWR#Quality

Any aspect of an Entity (but not a part of it), which cannot exist without that Entity. For example, the way the surface of a specific PhysicalObject looks like is a Quality, while the encoding of that Quality into e.g. a PhysicalAttribute should be modeled as a Region. From the design viewpoint, the Quality-Region distinction is useful only when individual aspects of an Entity are considered in a domain of discourse. For example, in an automotive context, it would be irrelevant to consider the aspects of car windows for a specific car, unless the factory wants to check a specific window against design parameters (anomaly detection). On the other hand, in an antiques context, the individual aspects for a specific piece of furniture are a major focus of attention, and may constitute the actual added value, because the design parameters for old furniture are often not fixed, and may not be viewed as 'anomalies'.
Is defined by
http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr
has super-classes
entity c
has sub-classes
property c

Samplec back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: http://www.w3.org/ns/sosa/Sample

A Sample is the result from an act of Sampling.
Feature which is intended to be representative of a FeatureOfInterest on which Observations may be made.
Is defined by
http://www.w3.org/ns/sosa/
Example
A 'station' is essentially an identifiable locality where a sensor system or Procedure may be deployed and an observation made. In the context of the observation model, it connotes the 'world in the vicinity of the station', so the observed properties relate to the physical medium at the station, and not to any physical artifact such as a mooring, buoy, benchmark, monument, well, etc.
A statistical sample is often designed to be characteristic of an entire population, so that observations can be made regarding the sample that provide a good estimate of the properties of the population.
has super-classes
Feature Of Interest c, Result c
is in domain of
has sample relationship op, is feature of interest of op, is result of op, is sample of op
is in range of
has feature of interest op, has result op, has sample op, related sample op

In the context of the Arrowhead Framework a Service is the information exchanged from a providing system to a consuming system. is based on a number of service orientation principles derived from high level objectives and properties of the Arrowhead framework can be realized by an arbitrary number of service producers and service consumers a system can consume a number of services, process and provide other services to fulfil a more complex task can only be provided by technical systems can support operational activities within business processes can support non-functional requirements, such as real-time can have stakeholders, with an interest in business benefit, in one or more specific area of interest can have an appointed stakeholder, responsible for the governance of the Service (definition, development). (Source: Arrowhead Framework Definitions V2.4 & Arrowhead Device Registry Presentation)

situationc back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-PWR#Situation

A view, consistent with ('satisfying') a Description, on a set of entities. It can also be seen as a 'relational context' created by an observer on the basis of a 'frame' (i.e. a Description). For example, a PlanExecution is a context including some actions executed by agents according to certain parameters and expected tasks to be achieved from a Plan; a DiagnosedSituation is a context of observed entities that is interpreted on the basis of a Diagnosis, etc. Situation is also able to represent reified n-ary relations, where isSettingFor is the top-level relation for all binary projections of the n-ary relation. If used in a transformation pattern for n-ary relations, the designer should take care of creating only one subclass of Situation for each n-ary relation, otherwise the 'identification constraint' (Calvanese et al., IJCAI 2001) could be violated.
Is defined by
http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr
has super-classes

has sub-classes

system web application description w a d lc back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#System_WebApplicationDescription_WADL

Description of an Arrowhead compliant software system in terms of the Web Application Description Language WADL. The Web Application Description Language (WADL) is a machine-readable XML description of HTTP-based web services. WADL models the resources provided by a service and the relationships between them. WADL is intended to simplify the reuse of web services that are based on the existing HTTP architecture of the Web. It is platform and language independent and aims to promote reuse of applications beyond the basic use in a web browser. WADL is the REST equivalent of SOAP's Web Services Description Language (WSDL), which can also be used to describe REST web services. Sources: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_Application_Description_Language Sun Microsystems (31 August 2009). "Web Application Description Language: W3C Member Submission 31 August 2009". World Wide Web Consortium. Retrieved 12 August 2012. World Wide Web Consortium (14 October 2009). "Team Comment on the "Web Application Description Language" Submission". World Wide Web Consortium. Retrieved 12 August 2012. Lawrence Mandel (29 May 2008). "Describe REST Web services with WSDL 2.0: A how-to guide". IBM. Retrieved 12 August 2012.

a h system documentation document c
has sub-classes
a h authorization system w a d l c, a h orchestrator w a d l c, a h service registry w a d l c

documents a h service methodop back to ToC or Object Property ToC

IRI: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#documentsAHServiceMethod

Relation between an Interface Design Description document (of a specific service) and a method of this service. The relation expresses that the IDD document documents the methods of the service the IDD belongs to. With this, a consistency check would be possible: IF a service S has a method M AND the IDD IDD_S is part of the service documentation of S (i.e. IDD_S is the IDD of S) THEN IDD_S should contain a documentation of M.
has super-properties
documents service part op
has domain
interface design description i d d c
has range
method c

Relation expressing that a software system produces a service. refers toop back to ToC or Object Property ToC

IRI: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#refersTo

describes the relation between two documentation documents that one document refers to another document. To our best knowledge, the following relations hold between different types of documentation documents: - an IDD refers to exactly one SD. - an SD is referred to by one or more IDD (each stating a way of implementing the service with a specific technolopgy (Source: Arrowhead Framework Definitions V2.4)) - an IDD refers to at most one CP (if it not refers to a CP, then the IDD contains all CP information by itself) - an IDD refers to n SP, 0 <= n (if it not refers to a SP, then the IDD contains all SP information by itself) - a SySD refers to one or more IDDs (that is, a system produces one or more services). - a SySDD refers to one or more SySD's. (Remark HB: I don't understand this. How can one concrete white box description of a system fulfill (support / implement) different black box descriptions of systems? The other way around seems to be possible as between SDs and IDDs). - an SoSD refers to n SySD's. - an SoSDD refers to n SoSD's. - an SoSDD refers to n SySD's. - an SoSDD refers to n SySDDs.
has sub-properties

refers to c pop back to ToC or Object Property ToC

IRI: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#refersToCP

an Interface Design Description (IDD) can refer to a Communication Profile (CP). No other documentation document can refer to a CP. Hence the domain of this object property is the class of IDDs. An IDD can refer to a CP, but this is not mandatory. CPs are intended to be used in cases in which several services use the same CP. Then the CP information should be extracted to an CP document and the IDDs of all services that use this CP shall refer to this CP. If the CP is unique for a specific service, the CP information can directly be included in the IDD. If the IDD refers to a CP, this must be a unique reference. That is, one IDD must not refer to different CPs. Hence this object property is functional. (If the service could be implemented using different communication technologies, each implementation would need an own IDD!!).

has characteristics: functional

has super-properties
refers to op
has domain
interface design description i d d c
has range
communication profile c p c

refers to s pop back to ToC or Object Property ToC

IRI: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#refersToSP

an Interface Design Description (IDD) can refer to a Semantic Profile (SP). No other documentation document can refer to a SP. Hence the domain of this object property is the class of IDDs. An IDD can refer to a SP, but this is not mandatory. SPs are intended to be used in cases in which several services use the same SP. Then the SCP information should be extracted to an SP document and the IDDs of all services that use this SP shall refer to this SP. If the SP is unique for a specific service, the SP information can directly be included in the IDD. References to SPs are not necessarily unique for an IDD. That is, different methods of the service documented by the IDD can use different Semantic Profiles.
has super-properties
refers to op
has domain
interface design description i d d c
has range
semantic profile s p c
